INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (338, 1, '2012-03-19 18:58:58', '2012-03-19 18:58:58', '<strong><span style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;"><span style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Self-Assembly: From Bio-Colloids to Nano-Engineering</span></span></span></strong>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;"><span style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;">July 22-27, 2012\r\nBifrost University, Iceland</span></span>\r\n\r\n[FANCY-IMG-SHOW:GALLERY4]\r\n<h2>About this Conference</h2>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Synopsis</strong></span>:\r\nMolecular association in solution, involving self-assembly, precipitation, complexation etc., is a fundamental process in many areas, ranging from biology to materials science. Resulting structures, being equilibrium states or kinetically trapped, often occur on the colloidal or "nano" length scale, 1 nanometer - 1 micrometer. These resulting colloidal or nanostructures are direct consequences of intermolecular interactions on the shorter, molecular length scale. Hence to understand such systems requires characterization on a wide range of length and time scales, often using a combination of several experimental techniques and computer simulation. This involves also macroscopic length scales, on which very complex viscoelastic flow behavior often can be observed.</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">Self-assembled nanostructured materials are ubiquitous in a wide range of industries, covering areas such as drug delivery, home &amp; personal care, nanotechnology, foods, coatings etc. For the synthesis of many novel nano-materials self-assembly or controlled precipitation is of fundamental importance. It has been generally recognized that large scale fabrication of such materials cannot be done top-down. They have to be built from bottom-up.</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">The basic laws of nature, on the molecular length scale are known. What then characterizes contemporary science is the ability to analyze more and more complex systems, driven by access to a steadily increasing computational power and the development of new and sophisticated experimental tools. As a consequence, physics and physical chemistry are expanding into life science, creating new exciting areas like biological physics and colloidal biology.</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">IIn this conference, the third in the ECI <em>Association in Solution</em> series, we aim to bring together scientists from physics, chemistry, biology and engineering to discuss recent advances in the area of self-assembled and related systems.</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">This conference cuts across key, emerging areas in the biological, chemical, physical sciences along with nano- and micro-scale engineering. The topic is central to many major industries including food, cosmetics and consumer products, pharmaceuticals and energy (oil and gas production).</p>\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Organization</strong></span>\r\nThe conference chairs are\r\n<strong>Ulf Olsson</strong> (Department of Physical Chemistry, Lund University, Sweden)\r\n(e-mail: ulf.olsson@fkem1.lu.se)\r\nand\r\n<strong>Norman Wagner</strong> Department of Chemical Engineering, University of Delaware, USA)\r\n(e-mail: wagnernj@udel.edu)\r\n\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Steering Committee</strong></span>\r\nMembers of the Steering Committee are <strong>Lise Arleth</strong> (Copenhagen University, Denmark), <strong>Seyda Bucak</strong> (Yeditepe University, Turkey), <strong>Bernard Cabane</strong> (ESPCI, France), <strong>Jan Dhont</strong> (Forschungszentrum Jülich, Germany), <strong>Alex Evilevitch</strong> (Carnegie Mellon University, USA), <strong>Masayuki Imai</strong> (Ochanomizu University, Japan), <strong>Matt Lynch</strong> (Procter &amp; Gamble, USA), <strong>Robert Prud\'homme</strong> (Princeton University, USA), <strong>Kathleen Stebe</strong> (University of Pennsylvania, USA), <strong>Greg Warr</strong> (University of Sydney, Australia) .\r\n<h2>Abstract Submission</h2>\r\nAbstracts of approximately 300 words should be submitted as soon as possible and no later than <strong>April 15, 2012 for oral presentations</strong> and <strong>April 30, 2012 for poster presentations</strong>. The abstract should include both significance of the research as well as results that will be discussed in order to allow a scientific assessment of the work by the organizers. Abstracts should be submitted electronically following the instructions given in <a href="http://www.engconf.org/12asabsf.html"><strong>On-line Abstract Submission</strong></a>. If unable to submit the abstract electronically, please contact the ECI (<a href="mailto:info@engconfintl.org">info@engconfintl.org</a>).\r\n\r\nA poster competition among graduate student submissions is planned.\r\n<h2>ECI Conferences General Information</h2>\r\n- <a href="../../information">General info here</a>\r\n<h2>Conference Venue</h2>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Bifröst University</strong></span><strong> (<a href="http://www.bifrost.is/english/" target="_blank">http://www.bifrost.is/english/</a>)</strong>\r\nBifröst University is a direct descendant of the Cooperative School, which was founded in Reykjavík in 1918 and began operations in December of that year. In the summer of 1955 the school moved to a newly built building in the countryside of Bifröst, roughly halfway between Reykjavík and Akureyri, and it has been there ever since. The move was a turning point in the history of the school. The school was reshaped and completely reorganized as a boarding school, and as the faculty and student numbers grew, the university village of Bifröst slowly took shape. The Cooperative School changed its name to the Cooperative University in 1988, to Bifröst School of Business in 2000, and to Bifröst University in 2006. These many changes reflect the tremendous growth and development of the Icelandic higher educational system over the last few decades.</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">Today, Bifröst\'s strongest enrollments are for its three-year bachelor\'s degrees, and since 2003, Bifröst offers master\'s degree programs as well. The number of students studying at Bifröst has grown quickly in recent years, from 120 students in 1998 to approximately 1200 at the beginning of 2008. Some are distance-learning students, but many students and faculty live on or near campus. Shops, the cafe, sports facilities, laundry, and banking facilities are all on campus. The opening of the Hvalfjarðargöng tunnel in 1998 brought Bifröst within an hour and a half\'s driving distance of Reykjavík and had a major impact on life in the entire Borgarfjörður region.</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">Business education and social affairs was the school\'s focus from the beginning, and Bifröst has always been progressive and innovative. In recent years, Bifröst has continued to be an "early adopter" among Icelandic universities by reducing class sizes, focusing on practical assignments rather than exams, and increasing the use of computers and online communication in teaching. Today Bifröst University is an institution of considerable diversity, which offers its students quality training in business, law, and the social sciences, and prepares them for positions of responsibility and leadership both in Iceland and abroad.</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Local Activities</strong></span>\r\nBifröst is an ideal stopover for travelers in the Borgarfjordur district. The craters, lava field, and mountainous surroundings are unique. The 3600 years old lava field is vegetated with mosses, lichens, berries, willow, and birch and there are a few hiking trails through this rugged and impressive landscape. The area around Bifröst offers a great variety of interesting sights. It is an ideal place to enjoy nature\'s refreshing beauty. Some of the unique destinations in the area include:</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><strong>Arnarstapi and Hellnar</strong>- In 1979 a total of 58 hectares of the coast at Arnarstapi and Hellnar were declared protected areas. The surf has sculpted strange cliff formations there and the source of the 3,900 year old Hellnahraun lava field is a crater near Jokulhals, now covered by a glacier. A cold spring dedicated to the Holy Virgin, where she appeared in the past, is to be found at the lava\'s edge. Few families live in Arnarstapi year-round, but in the summer the place is teeming with a myriad of birds including ravines and kittiwakes. Most locals engage in small-boat fishing or living in summerhouses. A fair distance off the coast is a single rock, surrounded by sea, called Arnarklettur. At Hellnar there is a natural sea port, which was one of the largest on the peninsula in past centuries and many relics in the area are indicative of its history. In Hellnar spectacular and beautiful cliffs rise directly from the ocean. You can also find Grouholl beach, a freestanding rock that extends east of the bay called Valasnos, Iceland\'s most peculiar cave called Badstofa, and the Hellnar church which was built in 1945 on a picturesque site where a church was first raised in 1833.</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><a href="http://www.engconf.org/staging/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/12asbaula.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-347" title="12asbaula" src="http://www.engconf.org/staging/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/12asbaula.jpg" alt="" width="275" height="183" /></a> <strong>Baula</strong>- This beautiful cone shaped mountain is very conspicuous in the background. According to the legend, there is a pond containing a wishing stone on top of it. The larger of the two main craters and Mt. Baula are well worth climbing on a fine day and can be conquered from different approaches. The most common trail lies from the farm called Dalsmynni up through Bjarnadalur and then up the mountain on the south side. The lava field and the craters are a nature reserve. The mountain is quite steep and hikers should expect at least eight hours round trip.</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><strong>Búðardalur</strong>- Is a small village at the head of Hvammsfiordur Bay. Búðardalur has a long history, dating from the time of the first settlements in Iceland and its name means "Camp Valley." Búðardalur is the commercial centre for the county and boasts of one of the most advanced dairies in Iceland. It is renowned for its ardent efforts to create new milk products and has won many prizes in Iceland and in Europe. Many interesting places of interest / historical sites can be explored near Búðardalur, and a number of rivers and lakes offer excellent trout, char, and salmon fishing. A short distance from Búðardalur lies the site of the former siege of Erik the Red, who went from there to discover Greenland. He was the father of Leifur "Heppni" Eiríksson (Leif the Lucky) who went on and discovered America ahead of Columbus.</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><strong>Búðir</strong>- It is believed that fishing vessels have been making their landing at Búðir all the way back to when Iceland\'s first inhabitants made their way there across the ocean. Today the small hamlet of Búðir along with Hótel Búðir is a center of attraction in Snæfellsnes. Hotel Budir is undoubtedly one of the most beautiful countryside hotels in Iceland, just a short drive from Reykjavik. Hotel Budir is situated on the southwestern shores of Snaefellsnes peninsula, an area of Iceland which is renowned for its natural beauty, the impressive glacier-topped Snaefellsjokull volcano, and the Budir-estuary which meanders into the vast Faxafloi-Bay where a number of seals reside. Hotel Budir\'s restaurant, arguably one of the most romantic restaurants in Iceland, has been referred to as "The Mecca of Icelandic cooking", due to its unique and delightful cuisine.</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><a href="http://www.engconf.org/staging/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/12asvolcano.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-348" title="12asvolcano" src="http://www.engconf.org/staging/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/12asvolcano.jpg" alt="" width="271" height="210" /></a> <strong>Grábrók Volcano</strong>- This volcano has a magnificent view from the top that encompassing Norðurárdalur and the encircling mountains. A brisk walk from Bifröst campus to the top of the volcano and back again takes about 40 minutes. To the west of Grábrók is another volcano called Grábrókarfell. It is fairly easy to walk around both of these old volcanoes.</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><strong>Hraunfossar</strong>- (Meaning "lava falls") is an intriguing series of springs coming out of the Hallmundarhraun lava flow appearing like a long 900m strand of cascades laced within the rough grooves of the lava. These waterfalls were formed from an eruption of one of the volcanoes lying under the glacier Langjökull. The waterfalls pour into the Hvítá river from ledges of less porous rock in the lava.</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><strong>Surtshellir</strong>- (Surt\'s Cave) is in the Hallmundarhraun lava field and is the deepest and most renowned cave in Iceland. The total length of this cave is approximately 1,970 m. Along with the cave, Stefanshellir, which is a direct continuation of Surtshellir to the northeast; they are by far the longest caves of the country at 3,500 m. in total. The Icelandic Book of Settlements (Landnáma) says that the cave is named after the giant Surtur and that poets composed verses in his honor and recited them at the mouth of the cave. A part of the cave shows signs of human habitation in the past. The innermost part, where the ceiling is lower, is called "The Ice Cave", where one usually sees remarkable ice formations, ice candles and columns, sometimes all the way up to the ceiling.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>General Information and Travel Logistics</h2>\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Flights</strong></span> Iceland is easily reached via air and the main international airport is Keflavík, located in the southwest of the country about 40 km from Reykjavík. Approximate flight times from several cities are:\r\nCopenhagen, London, Frankfurt, Paris, Amsterdam to Reykjavik - approx: 3 hrs\r\nNew York, Boston, Minneapolis to Reykjavik - approx: 5-6 hrs\r\n\r\n<strong>Icelandair</strong> maintains regular scheduled flights to Iceland from the following cities:\r\nAll year: London, Glasgow, Copenhagen, Manchester, Oslo, Paris, Stockholm, Amsterdam, Frankfurt, Boston, New York and Seattle.\r\n<strong>Seasonal</strong>: Minneapolis / St. Paul, Toronto, Orlando, Halifax and Helsinki.\r\n<strong>Summer</strong>: Alicante, Barcelona, Bergen, Berlin, Billund, Stavanger, Madrid, Milan and Munich.\r\n\r\n<strong>Iceland Express</strong> maintains regular scheduled flights to Iceland from the following cities:\r\nAll year: London (Gatwick airport), Copenhagen, Berlin, New York and Warsaw.\r\nSummer: Aalborg, Alicante, Barcelona, Basel, Billund, Bologna, Boston, Chicago, Edinburgh, Frankfurt (Hahn airport), Friedrichshafen, Gothenburg, Krakow and Paris, Oslo, Stockholm and Winnipeg.\r\n\r\n<strong>SAS</strong> maintains regular scheduled flights to Iceland from Oslo.\r\n<strong>Delta Airlines</strong> Maintains regular scheduled flights to Iceland from JFK.\r\n\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Visas</strong></span>\r\nIndividuals should check www.utl.is to see whether they need to apply for a visa from an Icelandic consulate before arriving. The fee varies depending on nationality, and the visa typically allows a three-month stay.\r\n\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Electrical Current</strong></span>\r\nThe electric current in Iceland is 220volts, 50 HZ AC. Europlug/Schuko-Plug (CEE types)\r\n\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Currency</strong></span>\r\nThe Icelandic monetary unit is the "króna." Coins are in denominations of 100 kr., 50 kr., 10kr, 5 kr. and 1 kr. Bank notes are in denominations of 5000 kr., 2000 kr., 1000 kr., and 500 kr. All Icelandic banks provide foreign exchange and are generally open on weekdays from 09:15 to 16:00. For exchange rates visit the Central Bank of Iceland\'s website (http://www.sedlabanki.is/?PageID=183)\r\n\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Language</strong></span>\r\nThe official language of Iceland is Icelandic. Most people there can speak English and Danish and because of their Danish knowledge also understand Swedish and Norwegian. Even though the majority of Icelanders are competent in English, English-speaking visitors to the country should take the time to learn "thank you" in Icelandic for their trip.\r\n\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"> <strong>Weather</strong></span>\r\nThanks to the Gulf Stream, Iceland enjoys a cool temperate ocean climate: cool in summer and fairly mild in winter. However, the weather is very changeable and visitors should be prepared for the unexpected. When travelling in Iceland you should bring along lightweight woolens, a sweater or cardigan, a rainproof (weatherproof) coat, and sturdy walking shoes.\r\nFor specific weather information in English visit the Icelandic Meteorological Office\'s website (<a href="http://www.vedur.is/english" target="_blank">www.vedur.is/english</a>)\r\n\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Additional Resources</strong></span>\r\n<a href="http://www.icetourist.is/" target="_blank">www.icetourist.is/</a>\r\n<a href="http://www.westiceland.is/" target="_blank">www.westiceland.is</a>\r\n<a href="http://www.bifrost.is/english/" target="_blank">www.bifrost.is/english/</a>\r\n<a href="http://www.tripadvisor.com/Tourism-g189952-Iceland-Vacations.html" target="_blank">www.tripadvisor.com/Tourism-g189952-Iceland-Vacations.html</a> .\r\n<h2>Request for Next Mailing</h2>\r\n- <a href="https://participants.engconfintl.org/source/custom/mailing.cfm">Submit request</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Association in Solution III', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'association-in-solution-iii', '', '', '2012-03-19 20:48:06', '2012-03-19 20:48:06', '', 16, 'http://www.engconf.org/staging/?page_id=338', 5, 'page', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (353, 1, '2012-03-19 19:30:30', '2012-03-19 19:30:30', '<strong>New Trends in Characterizing Microstructure, Interactions &amp; Properties</strong>\r\n\r\nAn ECI Conference\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;"><strong></strong> <em>July 30 - Aug 3, 2012</em>\r\nTomar, Portugal</span>\r\n<h2>About this Conference</h2>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Conference Goals</strong></span>\r\nThe characterization of biological complex fluids such as proteins, DNA etc. is emerging as a rapidly evolving field. Understanding and establishing the structure-property relationships in such systems and understanding interactions in complex biopharmaceutical formulations is key to designing novel drug delivery mechanisms and new therapeutic solutions. However, most of these systems have their unique characterization challenges such as, small sample volumes, high sensitivity to any applied shear, external conditions etc. Also it is of primary importance to characterize the microstructure and interactions either in-vivo or in environments that very closely mimic the biological environment of interest. The need to characterize such complex fluids/soft matter systems also extends to other industrial sectors such as foods and personal care and some of the characterization challenges and limitations of current techniques remain quite similar across biopharmaceuticals, foods &amp; personal care industries.</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">These challenges have led to a number of different developments in novel characterization techniques, ranging from particle tracking microrheology to microfluidics and MEMS-based techniques. A key challenge in proper application/refinement of these devices and the development of new ones lies in the ability to adequately understand the requirements from an industrial application perspective and ensure that the generated insights directly impact on the fundamental understanding required for generation of design rules for product &amp; process design (therapeutic protein solutions, food systems etc). <a name="sessions"></a></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">This meeting, the first of its kind, will focus on bringing together a wide range of multi-disciplinary groups from academia and industry with a view to discussing key challenges, recent developments, and future trends in characterization of biological complex fluids. Some of the key areas of focus for the meeting will be novel characterization techniques focused on characterization of :</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Proteins</li>\r\n	<li>Biological Polyelectrolytes</li>\r\n	<li>Complex Bio-Pharmaceutical Formulations</li>\r\n	<li>Microbial Communities and Biofilms</li>\r\n	<li>Membranes</li>\r\n	<li>Cellular Biophysics and Multicellular Dynamics</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIn addition, there will be an industry-focused session on:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Characterization challenges in the Bio-pharmaceutical, Food &amp; Personal Care industry</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe following is a partial list of confirmed invited speakers (excluding Chair, Co-Chair &amp; Steering Committee Members)\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Confirmed Invited Speakers (Partial List)</strong></span>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Rossitza Alargova (Vertex Pharma)</li>\r\n	<li>Giuseppe Battaglia (Sheffield University)</li>\r\n	<li>Andreas Bausch (Technical University of Munich)</li>\r\n	<li>Sibani Lisa Biswal (Rice University)</li>\r\n	<li>Victor Breedveld (Georgia Institute of Technology)</li>\r\n	<li>Jonathan Cooper (University of Glasgow)</li>\r\n	<li>Tapan Das (Pfizer)</li>\r\n	<li>Kenneth Dawson (University College Dublin)</li>\r\n	<li>Aristide Dogariu (University of Central Florida)</li>\r\n	<li>Patrick Doyle (Massachusetts Institute of Technology)</li>\r\n	<li>Isabelle Dufour (IMS, Bordeaux)</li>\r\n	<li>Eric Furst (University of Delaware)</li>\r\n	<li>James Harden (University of Ottawa)</li>\r\n	<li>Steve Harding (University of Nottingham)</li>\r\n	<li>Robert Leheny (Johns Hopkins University)</li>\r\n	<li>Alex Levine (University of California Los Angeles)</li>\r\n	<li>Tom Lubensky (University of Pennsylvania)</li>\r\n	<li>Fred MacKintosh (Vrije University)</li>\r\n	<li>Satish Mallaya (Bristol Meyers Squibb)</li>\r\n	<li>Scott Manalis (Massachusetts Institute of Technology)</li>\r\n	<li>Vincenzo Martorana (CNR)</li>\r\n	<li>Tom Mason (University of California Los Angeles)</li>\r\n	<li>Aline Miller (University of Manchester)</li>\r\n	<li>Daisuki Mizuno (Kyushu University of Technology)</li>\r\n	<li>Taco Nicolai (Le Mans)</li>\r\n	<li>Carsten Olbrich (Bayer Healthcare Pharmaceuticals)</li>\r\n	<li>Vladimir Razinkov (Amgen, TBC)</li>\r\n	<li>Christian Rischel (Novo Nordisk)</li>\r\n	<li>Christopher Roberts (University of Delaware)</li>\r\n	<li>Frank Scheffold (University of Fribourg)</li>\r\n	<li>Peter Schurtenberger (University of Lund)</li>\r\n	<li>Peter So (Massachusetts Institute of Technology)</li>\r\n	<li>Todd Squires (University of California Santa Barbara)</li>\r\n	<li>Daphne Weihs (Technion)</li>\r\n	<li>Justin Cooper White (University of Queensland)</li>\r\n	<li>Kimura Yasuyuki (Kyushu University of Technology)</li>\r\n	<li>Xue-Feng Yuan (University of Manchester)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Conference Organization</h2>\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Conference Chair</strong></span>:\r\n<strong>Samiul Amin</strong>, Malvern Instruments Limited, UK (Email:samiul.amin@malvern.com)\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Conference Co-Chair</strong></span>:\r\nProf. <strong>Michael Solomon</strong>, University of Michigan, USA (Email: mjsolo@umich.edu)\r\n\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Conference Scientific Steering Committee</strong></span>\r\nProf. <strong>Dave Weitz</strong>, Mallinckrodt Professor of Physics and of Applied Physics, Harvard University, USA\r\nProf. <strong>Gareth McKinley</strong>, Dept. Mechanical Engineering, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, USA\r\nProf. <strong>Christoph F. Schmidt</strong>, Dept. of Molecular and Cellular Biophysics, Georg August University, Germany\r\nProf. <strong>Jan Dhont</strong>, Head at IFF-Institute, Soft Condensed Matter, Germany\r\nDr. <strong>Jai A. Pathak</strong>, MedImmune, USA\r\nProf. <strong>Dganit Danino</strong>, Department of Biotechnology and Food Engineering, Technion, Isreal\r\nDr. <strong>Patrick T. Spicer</strong>, Complex Fluid Microstructures, Procter and Gamble Co., USA\r\n<h2>Abstract Submission</h2>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;"><span style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;">Original papers for presentations at the <a href="#header0">listed sessions</a> are invited. If you wish to be considered for an oral or poster presentation, please submit an abstract of approximately 300 words by <strong>December 15, 2011</strong>. Abstracts should be submitted electronically following the instructions given in <a href="http://www.engconf.org/12aeabsf.html"><strong>On-line Abstract Submission</strong></a>. If you encounter any problems with the submission process, contact Engineering Conferences International (ECI) at <a href="mailto:info@engconfintl.org">info@engconfintl.org</a>or 1-212-514-6760. All abstracts will be reviewed by the Conference Co-Chairs.</span></span>\r\n\r\nGraduate students and young investigators are particularly encouraged to present posters. The poster sessions will be an integral part of the conference.\r\n<h2>ECI Conferences General Information</h2>\r\n- <a href="../../information">General Information</a>\r\n<h2>Conference Venue</h2>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Tomar, Portugal</strong></span>\r\n<a href="http://www.engconf.org/staging/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/12aeimagesmall.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-359" title="12aeimagesmall" src="http://www.engconf.org/staging/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/12aeimagesmall.jpg" alt="" width="356" height="414" /></a> Situated in the geographic center of Portugal, Tomar (about 135 km northeast of Lisbon) was founded by the notorious Knights Templar in 1160. The Templars were part monks, part warriors and plotted crusades from Tomar for centuries. They established the beginnings of the Convento de Cristo, Tomar\'s most famous landmark, on a hill overlooking town. The Convento combines architectural styles from the 12th through 17th centuries. An ornate octagonal canopy protects the high altar of the Templo dos Templares, modeled after the Holy Sepulchre in Jerusalem, and the grounds of the convent contain eight cloisters embracing a variety of styles.</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">The Templars earned a reputation as ferocious fighters, and won the admiration and trust of both rich and poor. They served as protectors and transporters of Christian kings, power brokers and pilgrims and grew famous as bankers. The Templars acquired great wealth, but made many enemies in the process. Pope Clement V accepted accusations of heresy, blasphemy and sacrilege leveled against the Templars by Philip the Fair, king of France, and many Templars were imprisoned or executed. King Dinis of Portugal allowed them to regroup their forces under the new aegis of the Order of Christ. Prince Henry the Navigator became Administrator after the Templars became the Order of Christ and he used much their wealth to finance his explorations.</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">Tomar is divided by the River Nabão, the banks of which are dotted with weirs and wheels once used to water vegetable gardens and orchards. The irrigation techniques illustrate the Muslim tradition of hydraulic engineering. Most sights, accommodations and shops lie on the west bank of the river and the lush Parque Mouchão straddles the two banks. The ancient yet functional Ponte Velha (Old Bridge) connects the two. Tomar\'s main shopping thoroughfare is rua Serpa Pinto, known locally as Corre Doura. Outlets for folklore, pottery, copperware and wrought iron highlight it. Tascas and bars are scattered throughout the city, with some offering live music.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Sponsor Packages</h2>\r\n- <a href="http://www.engconf.org/staging/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/12aesponsorship.pdf">Biological &amp; Pharmaceutical Complex Fluids Sponsorship</a>\r\n<h2>Hotel and Transportation</h2>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Hotel dos Templários</strong></span>\r\n<a href="http://www.engconf.org/staging/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/12aeimagehotel.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-361" title="12aeimagehotel" src="http://www.engconf.org/staging/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/12aeimagehotel.jpg" alt="" width="275" height="215" /></a> Situated near the heart of Tomar\'s Old Town, the Hotel dos Templários is the largest hotel in the district. Many rooms offer views of the Convent of Christ and the public areas, including lounges and terrace-view dining rooms, are spacious. The hotel offers room service, laundry, a barbershop, a beauty parlor, a billiards room and baby-sitting. There are wide sun terraces, indoor and outdoor pools, a tennis court and a greenhouse. The hotel also has large gardens. Rooms have air conditioning, private bathrooms, televisions and minibars. Free parking is available. Visit <a href="http://www.hoteldostemplarios.pt/" target="_blank">http://www.hoteldostemplarios.pt</a> to see photos of the hotel.</p>\r\nFor more information on the area, please visit these web sites:\r\n<a href="http://www.slideshare.net/1950/convento-de-cristo-tomar-portugal-presentation" target="_blank">http://www.slideshare.net/1950/convento-de-cristo-tomar-portugal-presentation</a>\r\n<a href="http://www.golisbon.com/portugal/cities/tomar.html" target="_blank">http://www.golisbon.com/portugal/cities/tomar.html</a>\r\n<a href="http://www.sacred-destinations.com/portugal/tomar.htm" target="_blank">http://www.sacred-destinations.com/portugal/tomar.htm</a>\r\n<a href="http://www.sacred-destinations.com/portugal/tomar-convento-de-cristo-templars.htm" target="_blank">http://www.sacred-destinations.com/portugal/tomar-convento-de-cristo-templars.htm</a>\r\n\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Transportation</strong></span>\r\n<strong>By train from Lisbon</strong>:\r\nThe trip from Lisbon to Tomar takes approximately 1½ hours. Upon arrival at the Tomar train station, taxis are available for the one or two kilometer trip to the Hotel Dos Templarios.\r\n<strong>By automobile from Lisbon</strong>:\r\nThe rental car companies will provide maps and driving instructions. Allow between 1-1/2 - 2 hours for the trip, depending on traffic. The hotel provides free parking.\r\n<h2>Conferences Fees</h2>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;">The conference fee is all-inclusive. It includes registration, accommodations and meals, taxes and gratuities from dinner on Sunday through lunch on Thursday. Incidental fees (telephone calls, faxes, equipment rentals, bar, etc.) are billed to your personal account by the hotel. Conference fees will be posted in spring 2012 when the preliminary conference program is available. </span>\r\n<h2>Request for Next Mailing</h2>\r\n- <a href="https://participants.engconfintl.org/source/custom/mailing.cfm">Register for information</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Biological & Pharmaceutical Complex Fluids', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'biological-pharmaceutical-complex-fluids', '', '', '2012-03-19 20:48:34', '2012-03-19 20:48:34', '', 16, 'http://www.engconf.org/staging/?page_id=353', 6, 'page', '', 0); 
