INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (49, 1, '2012-03-12 16:56:53', '2012-03-12 16:56:53', '<span style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;"><strong>March 25-30, 2012</strong></span>\r\n\r\nIn Conjunction With The Seventh International Biofluid Mechanics Symposium <span style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;">(Ein Bokek, Dead Sea, Israel)\r\n(D. Elad, Tel Aviv Univ.; D. Bluestein, Stony Brook Univ.; D. Dooly, Imperial College London; M. Gharib, California Inst. Of Technology; P. Hunter, The Univ. of Auckland; M. Engelman, ANSYS, Inc.) </span>\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nCrowne Plaza Dead Sea, Ein Bokek, Dead Sea, Israel\r\n\r\nA Conference to Honor Shmuel Einav on the Occasion of his 70th Birthday\r\n\r\nProfessor Ada Yonath, the 2009 Nobel Chemistry Laureate from the Weizmann Institute of Science in Israel, will deliver the Keynote Lecture of the Opening Ceremony\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h4 style="text-align: left;"><strong>About This Conference</strong></h4>\r\n<img src="../../12adeinav.jpg" alt="" width="545" height="109" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><strong>The conference will pay tribute to Prof. Einav\'s important contribution to biofluid mechanics with special emphasis to cardiovascular bioengineering, and his leading role in development of the field of biomedical engineering in Israel and worldwide.</strong></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Conference Scope</strong></span>\r\nOngoing advances in software and the relentless increase in computer speed and memory has accelerated the development of multidisciplinary computational fluid dynamics (CFD) models to simulate complex transport phenomena in medicine and biology. A specific emphasis will be given to the development of new CFD tools along with increasingly powerful graphic software for data visualization, and the interrelationship between numerical and experimental methods. Modeling of complex flows allows for deep insight into many phenomena within any Biofluid system, thus enabling the exploration of new biological and physiological aspects, and providing an excellent tool for predicting performance of devices during the design stage while accelerating the approval phase through virtual testing and validation. Medicine and biology are now progressively entering into the in <em>silico</em> modeling era.</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">The conference will cover all aspects of fundamental and advanced state-of-the-art developments and applications of CFD tools in medicine, bioengineering and biology, from cellular to organ level and from physiology to medical devices that incorporate transport of fluids in rigid or compliant boundaries. Academic investigators, inventors and designers of medical and pharmaceutical devices, as well as regulation specialists will be exposed to a large variety of new CFD applications. Merging this conference with the Biofluid Mechanics Symposium will expand the meeting to include experts from all aspects of biofluid phenomena.</p>\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Technical Program</strong></span>\r\n<table width="90%">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="LEFT" valign="TOP" width="50%">\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Cardiovascular blood flow</li>\r\n	<li>Respiratory flow</li>\r\n	<li>Urinary flow</li>\r\n	<li>Reproductive biofluid</li>\r\n	<li>Flow in digestive system</li>\r\n	<li>Fluid-Structure Interaction (FSI)</li>\r\n	<li>Cerebrospinal fluid (CSF)</li>\r\n	<li>Fluid flow in bones and joints</li>\r\n	<li>Cellular and molecular transport</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n<td align="LEFT" valign="TOP" width="50%">\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Multi-scale modeling</li>\r\n	<li>Patient specific CFD</li>\r\n	<li>Imaging based CFD</li>\r\n	<li>CFD in medical devices</li>\r\n	<li>Micro- and Nano-Fluidic devices</li>\r\n	<li>CFD in pharmaceutical industry</li>\r\n	<li>Targeted drug delivery</li>\r\n	<li>Swimming &amp; Flying</li>\r\n	<li>Multi-Physics Problems</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;"><span style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Publications</strong></span>\r\nThe Journal of Biomechanics will publish a special issue on biofluid mechanics that will be composed of peer-reviewed articles and reviews of selected presentations. This issue is scheduled to appear in January 2013.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h4 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Conference Organization</strong></h4>\r\nChair: Prof. <strong>David Elad</strong>, Tel Aviv University, Israel [elad@post.tau.ac.il]\r\nCo-Chair: Prof. <strong>Danny Bluestein</strong>, Stony Brook University, USA [danny.bluestein@sunysb.edu]\r\nCo-Chair: Prof. <strong>Denis Doorly</strong>, Imperial College London, UK [d.doorly@imperial.ac.uk]\r\nCo-Chair: Prof. <strong>Morteza Gharib</strong>, California Institute of Technology, USA [mgharib@caltech.edu]\r\nCo-Chair: Prof. <strong>Peter Hunter</strong>, University of Auckland, New Zealand [p.hunter@auckland.ac.nz]\r\nCo-Chair: Dr. <strong>Michael Engelman</strong>, ANSYS, Inc., USA [Michael.Engelman@ansys.com]\r\n\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Scientific Committee</strong></span>\r\nKlaus Affeld, Medical University Berlin, Germany.\r\nDominique Barthès-Biesel, Université de Technologie de Compiegne, France.\r\nStanley Berger, University of California at Berkeley, CA, USA.\r\nChris Bertram, University of Sydney, Australia.\r\nJames Brasseur, Pennsylvania State University, PA, USA.\r\nJulyan Cartwright, CSIC-Universidad de Granada, Spain.\r\nKrishnan Chandran, University of Iowa, IA, USA.\r\nShu Chien, University of California San Diego, CA, USA.\r\nStephen Cowin, City College of the City University of New York, NY, USA.\r\nTimothy David, University of Canterbury, New Zealand.\r\nPeter Davies, University of Pennsylvania, PA, USA.\r\nNatacha DePaola, Illinois Institute of Technology, IL, USA.\r\nForbes Dewey, Massachusett